<BaseLayout
  title="Editorial Team | severancepayestimator.com"
  description="Meet the editorial team behind severancepayestimator.com — employment law and HR professionals who review all content for accuracy."
>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p class="byline">Last updated May 2026.</p>

  <p>
    All content on severancepayestimator.com is reviewed by experienced HR and employment law professionals before publication. Our editorial process prioritizes accuracy, plain-language explanation, and practical utility for employees navigating separation from employment.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Editorial Team</h2>

  <div class="profile">
    <p>
      Our editorial team includes certified HR professionals (SHRM-CP) with more than a decade of experience in human resources, compensation design, and employment law compliance — advising HR teams at companies ranging from 50 to 5,000 employees on separation policy design, WARN Act compliance, and offer letter best practices. This side of the team has held HR business partner and total rewards roles at regional financial services firms, administering severance programs during multiple restructuring events, including drafting separation agreements, coordinating with outside employment counsel, and managing ERISA-compliant severance plan documents. This expertise informs all calculator methodology, industry benchmark data, and legal content on the site.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="profile">
    <p>
      The team also includes paralegals specializing in employment law, with a focus on separation agreements, non-compete disputes, and wrongful termination matters — including experience working alongside employment attorneys at a regional plaintiff-side law firm, reviewing thousands of severance agreements and helping clients understand the practical implications of their options before signing. This side of the team focuses on the negotiation and review side of severance: what employees should look for in a separation agreement, how to identify problematic clauses, and when to involve an attorney, drawing on direct experience with real cases while staying accessible to employees without a legal background.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Editorial Standards</h2>
  <p>
    We are committed to producing content that is accurate, unbiased, and practically useful. Our standards include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Source transparency:</strong> All data claims are linked to or attributed to their primary source (BLS, SHRM, court filings, or statutes). We do not publish unsourced statistics.</li>
    <li><strong>Legal accuracy review:</strong> All content discussing specific legal rules (WARN Act thresholds, ADEA review periods, FLSA classifications, state-specific laws) is reviewed by a qualified HR professional or paralegal before publication.</li>
    <li><strong>No conflict of interest:</strong> Our editorial team does not accept payment from law firms, outplacement providers, or other parties with financial interests in reader decisions. Advertising on the site (Google AdSense) is served programmatically and does not influence editorial content.</li>
    <li><strong>Regular updates:</strong> Content is reviewed at least annually, or when significant legal changes (new court rulings, amended state laws) affect accuracy. The publication date on each page reflects the most recent review.</li>
    <li><strong>Clear disclaimer:</strong> We clearly state that our content is informational only and not a substitute for legal advice. We actively encourage readers to consult an employment attorney for decisions about their specific situation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections</h2>
  <p>
    If you believe any content on this site contains a factual error, please contact us at <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We investigate all correction requests and publish corrections promptly when errors are confirmed.
  </p>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    Content on this site is for informational purposes only. It does not constitute legal advice. The editorial team are HR and legal support professionals, not licensed attorneys.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
